# UI Design — Template Identity & Brand Coherence

## The Footer Closes the Brand, Not the Page

The footer background is always the **deepest dark tone of the palette**, regardless of whether the rest of the site is light or dark.

| Domain | Footer background |
|--------|------------------|
| Fashion | `#1C1C1E` charcoal |
| Tech | `#0f172a` deep navy |
| Home decor | `#2C1810` dark walnut |
| Organic | `#1A2E1C` deep forest |
| Beauty | `#1C0510` deep plum |
| Sports | `#050505` near-black |

Footer rules:
- Brand name in display font, generous size, full opacity
- Body text at `rgba(foreground, 0.35)` — readable, clearly subordinate
- Border separators at `rgba(foreground, 0.1)` — barely visible, structural only
- Column layout: brand tagline / shop links / help links

---

## Each Template Is a Distinct Brand, Not a Reskin

A customer buying gym gear thinks and feels differently from one buying skincare or artisan furniture. The template must match that mental state before a single word is read.

Every template must have:
- Its own brand name (e.g., Atelier Noir, NovaCommerce, Haven, Grove, Petal, Apex)
- Its own tagline — one sentence, domain-true
- Its own display font choice
- Its own image ratio decision
- Its own hover interaction style
- Its own badge shape

Sharing any of these across templates makes them feel like variations of the same thing. They must feel like competitors in their domain.

---

## Domain-Specific Data Fields in Product Cards

Products display different supporting metadata based on what the buyer needs to decide:

| Domain | Extra field shown |
|--------|------------------|
| Fashion | nothing (price + name is enough) |
| Tech | star rating + review count |
| Home decor | nothing (description-driven) |
| Organic | weight / quantity (e.g., "500 g jar") |
| Beauty | volume (e.g., "30 ml") |
| Sports | star rating + review count |

Show only what drives the purchase decision for that domain. Extra fields add noise.

---

## The Governing Test

Before shipping any template, ask:

> **Could a competitor in this domain have produced this?**

If **yes** — the template is generic. Return to palette, font, and interaction choices.

If **no** — color, type, image ratio, tone, and interaction have converged on a single coherent identity. That coherence is what makes it worth buying.

---

## Empty States Are Designed, Never Default

Every empty state (no results, empty cart, empty wishlist) gets:
1. A domain-appropriate icon
2. A short headline
3. A one-sentence sub-message
4. A single CTA

Never output `<p>No results.</p>` alone. The empty state is a brand moment.
